root.pub-comments: 'Arguments in favor of an "Austric" family of languages are here tested and rejected as inadequate' (206). 'This list, as complete and as accurate as a comparison of the sources permits, was included because, scattered over many places, it is nowhere available in such a unified form' and 'sincere thanks for their valuable suggestions are due to Professors Fay-Cooper Cole, Julian Bonfante, and Martin Sprengling' (206). Thomas A. Sebeok did not make a clear distinction between language and dialect in his tree. The decision to make a node a language or dialect was reached from research and judgement.
root.publications: Sebeok, Thomas A. 1942. An Examination of the Austroasiatic Language Family, Language, 3 edn., vol. 18, 206-217. Rochester, NY: Linguistic Society of America.

child.pub-comments: 'By eliminating two [Muṇḍa and Annam-Muong] of the three branches of the "Austroasiatic" sub-group, the latter simply becomes synonymous with "Mon-Khmer." This still leaves open the possibility, of course, that this sub-group with a single member may be related to the "Austronesian" sub-group with a great multitude of members, and that thus the "Austric" family may be genuine' (211).

child.pub-comments: 'While genetic connection between Mon-Khmer and Muṇḍa cannot be categorically denied, in the absence of proof or even good evidence the latter must be excluded from the Austroasiatic subgroup of the Austric family of languages' (211).

child.pub-comments: It must be noted that all of the languages in this subgroup are Sino-Tibetan. Austin Hale points this out on page 135 in the bibliography to his book, "Research on Tibeto-Burman Languages," published by Walter de Gruyter in 1982. child.pub-comments: It appears that 'Patan' may be referring to a region, of which there are many that are so named in Aghanistan, Nepal, and India. Pattani (ISO 639-3: lae) is spoken in a region called Pattan. Apatani (ISO 639-3: apt) is another Sino-Tibetan language, but is not in the Himalayish sub-grouping. Because of the uncertainty, both languages are listed.
